example.p:
Indeed, although we saw in that the sequences e^0,e^1,e^2,\ldots are linearly independent, shows that they are not spanning. Indeed,
W=\mathrm{span}\{e^0,e^1,e^2,\ldots\}
is a subspace of \mathrm{Seq}_{\mathbb{R}}, consisting exactly of the finitely supported sequences, i.e., those sequences that have only finitely many non-zero components. Thus, \{e^0,e^1,e^2,\ldots\} is a basis of W.

Since this is the general form of the elements of W, and since the two sequences starting with 1,0 and 0,1 are clearly linearly independent, it follows that
\{(1,0,1,1,2,3,\ldots),(0,1,1,2,3,5,\ldots)\}
is a basis of W.

Let S\subseteq \Mvec_{2,2}(\mathbb{R}) be the linearly independent set given by

  S=\left\{
  \begin{bmatrix}1\amp0\\0\amp0\end{bmatrix},
  \begin{bmatrix}0\amp1\\0\amp0\end{bmatrix}
  \right\}.

We enlarge S to a basis of M_{2,2}.
